ire, England, United Kingdom","Oxfordshire, England":"Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Arden","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name, either from the district of Arden in Warwickshire or from Arden in Bredbury (Cheshire). The first placename is thought to be derived from a Celtic word meaning ‘high place’, cognate with <i>Ardennes</i>, the name of a forested region on the borders between northeastern France and eastern Belgium. The second derives from Old English <i>hēah</i> ‘high’ + <i>worthign</i> ‘enclosed settlement’."],"variants":[{"name":"Harden","meanings":["English: variant of   Arden   with prosthetic <i>H-</i>.","English: habitational name, either from Haredene Wood in East Tisbury (Wiltshire), or from Haredon (in Ugborough, Devon). The first placename probably derives from Old English <i>hara</i> ‘hare’ + <i>denu</i> ‘valley’. The second is from Old English <i>hara</i> + <i>dūn</i> ‘hare hill’.","English: variant of   Harding  ."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Thomas de Arden was born in 1223 as the son of Thomas de Arden and Lucia. He married Rose Vernon before 1267, in Bringhurst, Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died before 1306, in Hanwell, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1223–Bef 1306":"1223–enne 1306","1223–1306":"1223–1306","1240–1331":"1240–1331","1240–1316":"1240–1316","1272–1320":"1272–1320","1195–1284":"1195–1284","–1216":"–1216","1284":"1284","1240":"1240","1195":"1195","1272":"1272","Bef 1306":"enne 1306","1316":"1316","Abt 1284":"umbes 1284","1216":"1216","Abt 1272":"umbes 1272","Bef 1267":"enne 1267","1235":"1235","1223":"1223","1320":"1320","1331":"1331","1306":"1306","Hanwell, Oxfordshire, England":"Hanwell, Oxfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Bringhurst Leicestershire England":"Bringhurst, Leicestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Oxfordshire, England":"Oxfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England"},"fi":{"1223–Bef 1306":"1223–ennen vuotta 1306","1223–1306":"1223–1306","1240–1331":"1240–1331","1240–1316":"1240–1316","1272–1320":"1272–1320","1195–1284":"1195–1284","–1216":"–1216","1284":"1284","1240":"1240","1195":"1195","1272":"1272","Bef 1306":"ennen vuotta 1306","1316":"1316","Abt 1284":"noin 1284","1216":"1216","Abt 1272":"noin 1272","Bef 1267":"ennen vuotta 1267","1235":"1235","1223":"1223","1320":"1320","1331":"1331","1306":"1306","Hanwell, Oxfordshire, England":"Hanwell, Oxfordshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Bringhurst Leicestershire England":"Bringhurst, Leicestershire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Oxfordshire, England":"Oxfordshire, Englanti, Yhdistyn